Anonymous Fri 04 Jan 2019 02:43:01 No.20431009 Report
Quoted By:
>>20428470
Some of that is style. I consider myself an impressionist, and direct a lot of attention to the way I want the look of a scene to make you feel as opposed to what it actually looks like. That much is deliberate. I am definitely prone to letting it overdevelop though, and I'd agree that the Degeneracy Pressure introduction is pretty fucking overdeveloped. Chapter 3 of Degeneracy is a much better execution of the same concept with a far more even burn. Lassiez Dare I'm pretty happy with period, but I understand if it isn't for everyone. I'll admit to having some favorite flavors of impression (usually drawn on from particularly fond memories), and the look and feel of Lassiez Dare is one of the highest on that list. I may have gone a bit far for people who don't share my particular affection for it.

>Can't speak for his characters and storytelling
Let me be the first to tell you I'm really not that good at either. Those skills are what I was most interested in developing with my /hmofa/ projects, and that remains so. So far I'm most proud of the first You Wouldn't Dare and Turkey Shoot as they're my best examples of complete stories with proper narrative structure (clear exposition, rising action, climax, etc) and some of my favorite character executions so far. Degeneracy Pressure has the potential to be strong if I can get the story after chapter 3 and tight as the story before it, but I've been drawing something of a blank for that. Silver Lining is an effort at writing a fun pulp fiction adventure that draws a proper narrative over a novel length. I've been happy with some if it and less thrilled with other parts. It's been drawing out more than I want it to rather than staying tight and exciting, so I'm going to have to do my best to mitigate that.
